Indexing query file

    Generate an index file and a defline file from your input FASTA query
    sequence file

    - Usage examples
    
        ex) This command generates index file from input query file using 
            the extracted GI numbers as query ID ("-u 1") and stores part of 
            deflines in the defline file ("-b 0").
            
            $ python seqindexer.py -i 30_real_seqs.fa -o 30_real_seqs.fa.idx 
              -d 30_real_seqs.fa.def -u 1 -b 0
              
            In file, "30_real_seqs.fa.idx":
                0       1714    32140163
                1841    1418    32140165
                3382    2341    32140167
                ...
            
            In file, "30_real_seqs.fa.def":
                32140163        >gi|32140163|ref|NC_004908.1|
                32140165        >gi|32140165|ref|NC_004909.1|
                32140167        >gi|32140167|ref|NC_004910.1|
                ...
              
              
        ex) This command generates index file from input query file using 
            the generated serial numbers as query ID ("-u 0"). The serial number 
            is started from "1". The defline file stores the full deflines 
            in the defline file ("-b 1").
        
            $ python seqindexer.py -i 100_simul_seqs.fa -o 100_simul_seqs.fa.idx 
              -d 100_simul_seqs.fa.def -u 0 -s 1 -b 1

            In file, "100_simul_seqs.fa.idx":
                0       1000    1
                1049    1000    2
                2102    1000    3
                ...
                
            In file, "100_simul_seqs.fa.def":
                1       >gi|15078713|ref|NC_003038.1|_1_0_0_1000_0_1000
                2       >gi|15078713|ref|NC_003038.1|_2_2_900_1900_900_1900
                3       >gi|15078713|ref|NC_003038.1|_3_2_1800_2800_1800_2800
                ...
   
    The option descriptions of "seqindexer.py" is like the below.

        -i: input query file
        -o: output index file
        -d: output defline file
        -u: unique query ID option, 0=serial number, 1=GI number
        -s: if serial number option is selected, you can optionally specify 
            a starting number
        -b: defline saving option, 0=part of defline, 1=full defline
        
        
        
        


